Context¶

When banks want to figure out who should get a credit card, they use a tool called a credit score. They take a look at your personal information to see how good you might be at paying back your debts. It's like a report card for your borrowing habits. This helps them decide if lending money to you is a smart choice, making sure they don't take on too much risk.

Download the data¶

https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/rikdifos/credit-card-approval-prediction/data

The purpose of this project:¶

Building machine learning models assists banks in making informed decisions about credit card eligibility, enhancing their ability to identify suitable applicants.

Main findings:¶

  • Roughly two-thirds of the dataset entries are from female individuals.
  • Both genders of clients own more properties than they do not.
  • The majority of both female and male clients fall under the categories of Working, Secondary/secondary special, Married, House/apartment.
  • The age distribution data shows that the largest segments are within the 24 to 44 years age range, peaking at 15.1% for the 34 to 39 years bracket, with a steady decline as age increases.
  • The work experience data reveals that a majority of observations, specifically over 53.5%, fall within the first 5 years of experience, followed by a substantial decrease in frequency with each subsequent experience bracket.
  • Among the dataset, most applicants fall within the income range of 110,000 to 140,000 (currency unknown), constituting over 24.6% of the total observations.
  • Random forest and XGBoost perform relatively well in prediction and have similar performance; however, the predictive power of these models is not particularly high.
  • According to the information value, most of the variables are not useful for prediction.
  • It is evident that the dataset is significantly imbalanced, necessitating further data collection and additional techniques to overcome problems caused by imbalanced datasets.

This project aims to assess the potential default risk for credit card applications, so the initial information provided by applicants is very important.

According to the Bank for International Settlements (BIS), the definition of default includes any assets that are more than 90 days past due; however, some financial institutions have reduced this threshold to 60 days, and this standard will be applied here.

In [5]:
# The clients who have not paid within 59 days at least once.
raw_data_part2["default"] = 0
raw_data_part2.loc[raw_data_part2["STATUS"].isin(["2", "3", "4", "5"]), ["default"]] = 1
raw_data_part2["default"] = raw_data_part2.groupby("ID")["default"].transform("sum")
raw_data_part2.loc[raw_data_part2["default"] > 0, ["default"]] = 1

# Merge two datasets based on ID
raw_data = pd.merge(raw_data_part1, raw_data_part2, on="ID", how="inner")

# Initial information provided by applications
data = raw_data.loc[raw_data.groupby("ID")["MONTHS_BALANCE"].idxmin()].reset_index(drop=True)

    total = sum(counts)
    percentages = [f"{100 * count / total:.1f}%" for count in counts]
    labels_with_percentages = [
        f"{label} ({percentage})"
        for label, percentage in zip(counts.index, percentages)
    ]
    plt.pie(counts)
    plt.legend(

    )

# Counting defaults

theVariables = [
    "gender",
    "car_YN",
    "property_YN",
    "income_type",
    "education_type",
    "family_type",
    "housing_type",
    "family_Num",
    "children_Num",
]

ds = data.loc[data["default"] == 1, theVariables]
ds["gender"] = ds["gender"].map({0: "Female", 1: "Male"})
ds["car_YN"] = ds["car_YN"].map({0: "No", 1: "Yes"})
ds["property_YN"] = ds["property_YN"].map({0: "No", 1: "Yes"})

plt.figure(figsize=(16, 9))
plt.suptitle(
    "Default counts for [gender,car_YN,property_YN,income_type,education_type,family_type,housing_type,family_Num,children_Num]",
    ha="center",
    fontsize=15,
)

for i in range(len(theVariables)):
    plt.subplot(3, 3, i + 1)
    plt.title(theVariables[i])
    counts = ds[theVariables[i]].value_counts()
    plt.barh(counts.index.astype(str), counts.values)

    for j, (value, count) in enumerate(zip(counts.index, counts.values)):
        plt.text(count, j, f"{count}", va="center", ha="left", fontsize=11)

    plt.tick_params(axis="both", labelsize=11)
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

Main Findings:

  • gender: There are 379 defaults for females and 237 for males.
  • car_YN: There are 392 defaults for individuals without a car and 224 for those with a car.
  • property_YN: Individuals with property have 365 defaults, and those without have 251.
  • income_type: Working individuals have the highest count of defaults with 306, followed by commercial associates with 143, pensioners with 130, and state servants with 37.
  • education_type: The majority of individuals who defaulted are found in the secondary or secondary special education category, totaling 402. A significant number, 171, have completed higher education.
  • family_type: Married individuals account for the highest number of defaults at 393. In comparison, there are 101 defaults among those who are single or not married.
  • housing_type: The majority of individuals with defaults reside in houses or apartments, numbering 540.
  • family_Num: Families with two members have the most defaults, with 313, followed by one-member families with 139. The number of defaults decreases as family size increases.
  • children_Num: A total of 431 individuals with defaults are without children, and defaults tend to decrease as the number of children in a family increases.

Main Findings:

  • Work experience ranging from 0 to 45 years will be used to construct the bins.
    • The outlier data point at -1005.597260 will not be considered.
    • A negative value signifies that an individual is currently unemployed. This group represents approximately 31.60% of the total observations. Since the work experience of these individuals is unknown, the variable will be excluded from the model.
  • Income ranging from 20000 to 1580000 will be used to construct the age bins.

# Functions to detect outliers
def outliersNumber_IQR(vec):
    pct25 = vec.quantile(0.25)
    pct75 = vec.quantile(0.75)
    iqr = pct75 - pct25
    upperLimit = pct75 + 1.5 * iqr
    lowerLimit = pct25 - 1.5 * iqr
    outliersNumber = sum((vec > upperLimit) | (vec < lowerLimit))
    outlierIndex = vec[(vec > upperLimit) | (vec < lowerLimit)].index
    return outliersNumber, outlierIndex


def outliersNumber_Std(vec):
    upperLimit = vec.mean() + 3 * vec.std()
    lowerLimit = vec.mean() - 3 * vec.std()
    outliersNumber = sum((vec > upperLimit) | (vec < lowerLimit))
    outlierIndex = vec[(vec > upperLimit) | (vec < lowerLimit)].index
    return outliersNumber, outlierIndex

# Functions to convert categorical variables to dummy variables
def categorical_to_dummy(mdlData, feature):
    tempDs = pd.get_dummies(mdlData[feature], prefix=feature).astype(int)
    # drop dummy with lowest frequency
    dropDum = f"{feature}_{mdlData[feature].value_counts().index[-1]}"
    tempDs.drop([dropDum], axis=1, inplace=True)
    return tempDs

# Function to evaluate models
def modelEvaluation(models, X_train=None, y_train=None, X_test=None, y_test=None):
    resultTable = {}
    predValue = {}

    for modelName, model in models:
        timeBeg = time.time()
        model.fit(X_train, y_train)
        y_pred = model.predict(X_test)
        f1 = metrics.f1_score(y_test, y_pred)
        precision = metrics.precision_score(y_test, y_pred)
        recall = metrics.recall_score(y_test, y_pred)
        timeDur = time.time() - timeBeg

        resultTable.update({modelName: [f1, precision, recall, timeDur]})
        predValue.update({modelName: y_pred})

    resultTable = pd.DataFrame(resultTable)
    resultTable.index = ["f1_score", "precision", "recall", "model_time"]
    predValue = pd.DataFrame(predValue)
    predValue["actual"] = y_test.reset_index(drop=True)

    print("models performance >>")
    display(resultTable.head())
    print("")
    print("predictions overview >>")
    display(predValue.head())

    return resultTable, predValue

# Function to visualize models performance
def modelVisualization(resultTable):
    modelNames = resultTable.columns
    [fig, axes] = plt.subplots(2, 2, figsize=(12, 6))

    axes[0, 0].bar(modelNames, resultTable.loc["f1_score"])
    axes[0, 0].set_title("f1_score")
    plt.sca(axes[0, 0])  # Set the current axis
    plt.xticks(rotation=30)

    axes[0, 1].bar(modelNames, resultTable.loc["precision"])
    axes[0, 1].set_title("precision")
    plt.sca(axes[0, 1])  # Set the current axis
    plt.xticks(rotation=30)

    axes[1, 0].bar(modelNames, resultTable.loc["recall"])
    axes[1, 0].set_title("recall")
    plt.sca(axes[1, 0])  # Set the current axis
    plt.xticks(rotation=30)

    axes[1, 1].bar(modelNames, resultTable.loc["model_time"])
    axes[1, 1].set_title("model_time")
    plt.sca(axes[1, 1])  # Set the current axis
    plt.xticks(rotation=30)

    fig.tight_layout()

# Function to perform GridSearchCV fit
def bestModel(modelInfo, modelParam):
    modelName = modelInfo[0]
    model = modelInfo[1]
    timeBeg = time.time()
    theSearch = GridSearchCV(
        model,
        modelParam,
        scoring=["f1", "precision", "recall"],
        cv=5,
        refit="f1",
        n_jobs=-1,
    )
    modelObjects[modelName] = theSearch.fit(X_train, y_train)
    timeDur = time.time() - timeBeg
    modelObjects[modelName + "Time"] = timeDur
    return modelObjects

# Function to extract scores from the GridSearchCV fit object
def estimationResult(modelObjects):
    theBestEstimators = {}
    theBestParameters = {}
    estimationCompare = {}
    modelNames = [v for v in modelObjects.keys() if not all(s in v for s in "Time")]
    for modelName in modelNames:
        cv_results = pd.DataFrame(modelObjects[modelName].cv_results_)
        best_estimator_results = cv_results.iloc[cv_results["mean_test_f1"].idxmax(), :]
        f1 = best_estimator_results.mean_test_f1
        precision = best_estimator_results.mean_test_precision
        recall = best_estimator_results.mean_test_recall
        timeDur = modelObjects[modelName + "Time"]
        estimationCompare.update({modelName: [f1, precision, recall, timeDur]})

        theBestEstimators[modelName] = modelObjects[modelName].best_estimator_
        theBestParameters[modelName] = modelObjects[modelName].best_params_

    estimationCompare = pd.DataFrame(estimationCompare)
    estimationCompare.index = [
        "mean_f1_score",
        "mean_precision",
        "mean_recall",
        "mean_model_time",
    ]

    return theBestEstimators, theBestParameters, estimationCompare

# Compute IV for all features
features = X_train.columns
target = y_train
IV = []
for feature in features:
    if feature not in ["ages", "income_Num", "family_Num", "children_Num"]:
        df_woe_iv = (
            pd.crosstab(X_train[feature], target, normalize="columns")
            .assign(woe=lambda x: np.log(x[1] / x[0]))
            .assign(iv=lambda x: (x["woe"] * (x[1] - x[0])))
        )
        df_woe_iv = df_woe_iv.replace({"woe": {np.inf: 0, -np.inf: 0}})
        df_woe_iv = df_woe_iv.replace({"iv": {np.inf: 0, -np.inf: 0}})
        df_woe_iv["iv_sum"] = df_woe_iv.iv.sum()
        IV.append(df_woe_iv["iv_sum"][0])
    else:
        IV.append(np.nan)
IV = pd.DataFrame(IV, features, columns=["iv"])
IV["power"] = IV["iv"] > 0.02
display(IV)

The Information Value (IV) is a metric that assesses a variable's predictive power.

Source: https://www.listendata.com/2015/03/weight-of-evidence-woe-and-information.html

Main Findings:

  • In conclusion, Random forest and XGBoost perform relatively well in prediction and have similar performance; however, the predictive power of these models is not particularly high.
  • According to the information value, most of the variables are not useful for prediction.
